    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay i understand. i'll keep my hands off it for now. i'm just curious though, why does it make that specific humming/vibrating noise if nothing is actually moving? like why doesnt it just be silent if the motor isnt turning?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That specific humming and vibrating noise happens because the motor is still receiving electrical power, but the magnetic fields inside it are fighting against each other or against mechanical resistance, creating a \"locked rotor\" condition. Even though the fan isn't spinning, the windings in the motor are trying to turn, generating heat and vibration through friction and magnetic attraction.\n\nThink of it like a giant, high-tech version of a **goblin's rusty gear**. You might imagine that if a goblin is stuck in a hole, they just sit there silently. But if you try to pull a goblin out of a hole with a rope that's tangled in a knot, the goblin will start to *vibrate* and *hum* with frustration as they struggle against the knot, even if they aren't moving forward. The motor is essentially a very angry, electric goblin trying to turn a bolt that is welded shut.\n\nThe vibration you feel is the motor trying to generate enough torque to break the seal, but it can't, so the energy turns into heat and sound instead of motion. If you were to touch it, you'd feel the heat radiating from that frustrated goblin trying to escape.\n\n**To answer your question:** It",
